column34: property_value:"When Woolley lists context only as 'Ur' on his object catalog cards he tends to mean that it was found somewhere within the confines of the city wall but no more specific than that. These are often surface finds that Woolley felt did not require more specific find spot information. Those found outside the city walls were typically recorded as 'brought in' followed by the name of the broad region from which they were brought in by the workers."
column54: property_value:"In the southeast portion of the mound of Ur
column55: Woolley excavated a large horizontal extent of domestic space roughly 115 x 85m. near the surface he found scattered Neo-Babylonian and Kassite remains and intrusive graves of the late periods but he did not publish these in detail nor are there any extant notes covering them. Instead
column56: Woolley's main goal was to uncover the best preserved floorplans of houses. These he found several meters down
column57: houses of the Isin-Larsa/Old Babylonian period. Because the Old Babylonian period was typically that associated with the potential time of Abraham
column58: Woolley used the abbreviation AH (Abraham's Housing) to refer to this excavation area.\r\n\r\nIn the course of excavation of the Isin-Larsa/Old Babylonian levels Woolley numbered 27 'houses
column59: ' or excavation units. He renumbered the houses for publication based on the overall plan
column61: and doors onto streets. In this way he showed there were 52 individual houses within his 27 excavation areas. However
column62: houses were frequently altered throughout period
column63: as families would knock out walls or block up doors
column64: and thus true house numbers are difficult to establish. Woolley mentions phases of rebuilding
column65: but states that he sought the best preserved floor plan and published the excavation of a particular house based on that plan alone. In some cases he noted deeper remains that may have gone back to the Ur III period. These levels he partially uncovered as he excavated graves beneath the Larsa period floors.\r\n\r\nA great deal of baked brick was in use for walls of the Isin-Larsa/Old Babylonian period. Some houses used it in the lowest portion of a wall
column66: but others used it for entire walls up to 3 meters in height. Town planning was not evident
column67: as streets tended to wander in narrow and winding paths. Corners where streets met were often rounded
column68: leading Woolley to surmise that this was to prevent problems with laden donkeys catching their wares on corners.\r\n\r\nMany houses had a domestic chapel within
column69: often with family burials beneath the floor. Communal chapels were also noted
column70: at least four being identified in the area. Finally
column71: Woolley believed that some buildings were specifically used for commercial activities (shops)
column72: though this is difficult to prove."

column11552: property_value:"The house was built relatively late in the history of the quarter. Whereas the original floor of No. 1 Broad Street (The School House) next door was flush with the offset of its outer wall
column11553: the original threshold of No. 1 Store Street was fifteen courses of burnt brick (1.35 m.) above that offset and was raised first 0.30 m. and later 1.10 m.
column11554: so that the street level rose nearly a metre and a half during the interval between the building of the School House and of this
column11555: and rose another metre during the lifetime of No. 1 Store Street. On the inside of the street wall there was an offset corresponding to the early threshold and in Room 8 there were remains of brick pavement at this level; in the same room
column11557: the existing pavement was 0.40 m. above the offset and so corresponded with the first raising of the front-door threshold. The internal walls had their foundations on the offset level
column11558: but some of them were re-built over older mud-brick walls following the same lines; the east (outer) wall had burnt brick foundations going down 0.80 m. lower and resting on mud brick and the west wall went down for 0.90 m. with mud brick below
column11559: while the street wall went down in burnt brick 1.20 m. below the door threshold. That the mud brick below the walls was not contemporary foundation is shown by the fact that its top was not flat and regular
column11561: so that the burnt brick above had had to be stepped down at intervals to secure a proper footing in the gaps. It follows therefore that the house as it has survived was a reconstruction of an older building of a more or less similar design
column11562: but that older building was of definitely earlier date than the quarter in general (i.e.
column11563: of the Third Dynasty rather than of the Larsa period) and the lack of any front door in its wall on Store Street implies a different orientation if not an altered street line. It is only the surviving building with which we are concerned.\r\n"

column15297: property_value:"The meaning of the excavation area abbreviation CLW is not precisely clear. Some references to it state that it is the central portion of the northeastern city wall
column15298: thus it might mean Central Long Wall. Field notes with the abbreviation
column15300: refer to excavation squares along the entirety of the edge of the mound where the outer city wall once stood and thus it more likely to refer to the City Long Wall as a whole.\r\n\r\nH.R. Hall dug a 12 meter trench across the city wall in 1919
column15301: but Woolley began his investigations of it in February of 1929. In a period of a few days he exposed 100 meters of the length of the wall behind his dig house. In the next season he set his workers to tracing the entirety of the wall
column15302: which ran approximately 2.5 miles around the city. To uncover it they simply followed the outer line of the wall to no great depth and made cross cut trenches to assess the width of the wall at intervals. Despite the great extent
column15303: the tracing of the wall took only one month. In a report sent from the field in February of 1930
column15305: \"...the wall is a complete ruin; not a vestige of the burnt-brick wall proper has been discovered and in few places does more survive than the weathered stump of the huge mud-brick rampart along which the wall originally ran.\"\r\n\r\nThe investigations showed the original wall to be between 25 and 34 meters wide and Woolley estimated that it once stood to a height of 8 meters. On the central portion of the east side
column15306: he found and excavated partial houses. Woolley believed that for portions of Ur's history
column15307: the backs of these houses formed the defensive wall itself. Many of the objects marked as CLW come from this specific area of houses along the wall
column15308: and this is likely the reason that CLW in abbreviation lists is said to be the central portion of the northeast city wall.\r\n\r\nThe sloping revetment that was often found in CLW squares was evidence of the bank of a canal running along the east side of the city. Some of the CLW squares also contained other excavation areas
column15309: such as the North and West harbors
column15325: that do not have a period designation"

column16108: property_value:"Nin-Gish-Zida Temple; Nin-Giz-Zid-Da Temple; Nin-Ezen Temple"
column16116: property_value:"The excavation area abbreviation NT refers to a successive series of small temples built very near the city wall in the southwestern portion of Ur. The temple nearest the surface was that built in the Neo-Babylonian period and attributable to the reign of Nebuchadnezzar. The excavation area abbreviation NT actually stands for Nebuchadnezzar's temple. No Persian period temple was found here but Persian burials infringed on the building (see area NTB).\r\n\r\nBeneath the Neo-Babylonian temple Woolley discovered another
column16117: similar temple of the Kassite period. This one seemed to have two phases of construction
column16118: one phase attributable to the reign of Kurigalzu. Beneath this sat another temple of the Isin-Larsa/Old Babylonian period
column16119: also with two phases. One of these dated to the reign of Rim Sin and the other to that of Sin-Iddinam. Yet another temple sat beneath
column16120: but this one was very fragmentary and difficult to map. It likely belonged to the Ur III period but little could be discerned.\r\n\r\nInscribed clay cones found in the Larsa levels give the name of the building as E-ni-gi-na and state that Rim-Sin restored this temple dedicated to Nin-gish-zida. Inscriptions in other levels show that this deity was honored here throughout the time periods but that Nin-Ezen (Ningizzida's consort) was also honored here in a kind of double shrine. Woolley suggested that another temple to Nin-Ezen appeared in the temenos area (see area SM) and that Ningizzida was the primary deity for this smaller temple in the southern city."
column16989: property_value:"Along the city wall (CLW) in the southeast Woolley came across a relatively large building and spent some time investigating it. Here he found clay cones of Rim-Sin and a foundation deposit mentioning that this king had dedicated the building to the god Enki. Thus Woolley referred to the building as the Enki Temple of Rim-Sin or simply the Rim-Sin Temple. Legrain lists the abbreviation RS but the code does not appear on any field catalogue cards.\r\n\r\nRim-Sin's ninth year is known as 'the year in which he built the temple of En-ki at Ur.' He probably made major restorations rather than founding the building
column16993: temple beneath. There are many inscribed bricks of this earlier king
column16994: but the early ground plan was mostly destroyed."
column17012: footnote:"partially published as the northern portion of EM"}
column17014: property_value:"The excavation area abbreviation DP probably stands for Dungi's Palace; Woolley believed the building with bricks marked e-hur-sag (thought to refer to Shulgi's palace) was too small to be what should be a grandiose building. Thus
column17015: he explored the area southeast of the giparu extensively looking for it. Most of his abbreviations for excavations in this area refer to the potential palace. When he found cylinders inscribed with the name of Shulgi beneath a partly ruined floor (excavation area abbreviation DT in the northwestern portion of area EH)
column17016: he thought he might have found it or at least indications of it. This building turned out to be a temple dedicated to Dimtabba (now read Nimintabba) and its very partial remains extended beyond the line of the Neo-Babylonian temenos wall to the west. Woolley continued to dig into this western area under a new excavation abbreviation
column17017: DP. This area did not reveal a palace or additional ruins of the Nimintabba temple
column17018: but instead it showed denuded domestic space related to Hall's Area A excavations. Area DP became the northern portion of area EM
column17019: but only partial houses are shown here along what Woolley termed Quality Lane. The houses here were never published in great detail
column17020: but many of the DP graves appear on the area EM map as falling along Quality Lane."
column17185: the dublalmah was originally a gateway onto the eastern corner of the ziggurat terrace. It expanded into a larger building in the Isin-Larsa/Old Babylonian period. It had multiple functions
column17187: through the centuries. An inscribed door socket of Amar-Sin found here refers to the building as the great storehouse of tablets and the place of judgment. It was thus essentially a law court
column17188: possibly with tablets recording judgments stored within. In Mesopotamia
column17189: an eastern gateway--in sight of the rising sun--was typically seen as a place of justice
column17190: and gateways were often places where witnesses or judges might hear claims.\r\n\r\nAfter the Ur III period the door onto the ziggurat terrace was sealed up and the dublalmah appears to have become a shrine
column17191: but it retained its name and probably its law court function. Kurigalzu made significant restorations to the building in the Kassite period and Woolley marveled at the well-constructed fully preserved arched doorway of this Late Bronze Age time. By the Neo-Babylonian period
column17192: the structure had essentially merged with the functions of the neighboring giparu."
column17279: footnote:"named for the ehursag but does not contain that building itself"}
column17285: property_value:"Area EH is located within the Neo-Babylonian temenos wall south of the giparu. There are many other area designations given to parts of this space (such as DP and LR)
column17286: but EH overall refers to the interior extent of the SW temenos wall from the south corner almost to the Nebuchadnezzar gate and extending east to the line of Pit F. Walls in the area were scattered and difficult to follow
column17287: so Woolley established a grid covering at least 55x100 meters in 5x5 squares. The grid is not well documented but publication shows that Woolley began numbers to the east
column17291: A therefore sits in the SE corner -- 11
column17292: T in the NW.\r\n\r\nThe abbreviation EH stands for E-Hur-sag but the building of that name does not lie within this excavation zone. Woolley did not believe that the building to the east of this area (partially dug by H.R. Hall in 1919) was the e-hur-sag
column17294: despite bricks with the inscription of the building being found there. Instead he called that building Hall's Temple (HT) and sought the palace in many other places inside the temenos. He eventually conceded that HT was indeed the e-hur-sag and published EH without reference to the abbreviation's original meaning.\r\n\r\nThe area Woolley called EH was the area Hall called the 'tomb mound' because it was relatively high ground in which he found a number of graves. Woolley showed that these were the remains of graves beneath the floors of houses dating from the Isin-Larsa to Kassite periods. EH in this time was likely an extension of the domestic area EM. In the Ur III period there appear to have been larger public buildings here
column17295: but their remains were spotty at best. Tablets from this area and area EM show that the residents of the domestic quarter in the Isin-Larsa/Old Babylonian period were likely temple workers."

column18415: property_value:"It is unclear what this excavation abbreviation refers to except that it is within area EH. Perhaps it is the lower right portion of the grid of 5x5 meter squares established over the EH area
column18416: making it the lower grid numbers. Woolley rarely used a grid
column18417: preferring to use architectural remains to guide his excavation
column18418: but when he did use a local grid
column18419: it was typically established in 5x5 meter individual squares and often numbered east to west and lettered south to north. These grid square number/letter combinations occasionally appear on artifact cards
column18420: but more often they do not
column18421: so LR may have been a general location code within the EH grid. Only four artifacts have the context designation LR and one of them makes it clear that the area is within EH
column18478: property_value:"The abbreviation DT stands for Dungi's Temple or Dimtabba Temple and this abbreviation is found within the larger EH excavation area; Woolley discovered cylinders inscribed with the name of Shulgi beneath a partly ruined floor in area EH and assigned the building it was associated with an excavation abbreviation of its own. The building's walls were almost completely destroyed
column18480: and thus were difficult to follow. They lay in the northwestern portion of area EH and originally defined a temple dedicated to the god Nimintabba (Woolley initially read the name as Dim-Tab-Ba). The ephemeral remains of the temple stretched underneath and beyond the Neo-Babylonian temenos wall and Woolley expanded excavation in search of the rest
column18481: but little more of the temple was found. The westward expansion of the excavation beyond the temenos wall became excavation area abbreviation DP."
column18505: property_value:"Unit R and S 9 in EH"
column18585: property_value:"The excavation area abbreviation HT stands for Hall's Temple because H.R. Hall had excavated parts of it in 1919. Hall called it Area (or Building) B and he found inscribed bricks in the paved floors of the building which indicated it was the ehursag
column18587: which was purported to be Shulgi's palace. Woolley
column18589: found inscribed bricks in the walls that mentioned Ur-Namma's temple of the moon god
column18590: and he concluded the building was actually a temple
column18591: dubbing the excavation area HT. He believed the actual ehursag palace to be located somewhere else within the temenos. Many of his subsequent excavation abbreviations attest to his search for the building
column18592: but he eventually agreed that HT was the ehursag itself.\r\n\r\nIn his fourth season
column18593: Woolley cleared the remaining extents of the building. He had already explored parts of the terrace wall on which it stood and came to find that it was part of the Ur III temenos wall. Along this wall near the ehursag Woolley found a deep well
column18594: at the bottom of which (13 meters down) were many inscribed clay cones."
column18614: property_value:"The excavation area abbreviation EM stands for Extra-Mural because this area lies outside of the southwest Temenos Wall. H.R. Hall investigated a portion of the high ground at this site (his Area A) in 1919
column18615: finding the remains of domestic structures. Taylor had also cut a trench here in 1853. Woolley first tested the ground early in 1926 (season 4) and then dug more completely in season 5
column18616: concentrating on about 60x40 meters of space and excavating to a depth of approximately 5 meters from the surface. He dug through Kassite and other late remains that were particularly fragmentary. He reported two Kassite houses (which he dubbed High House and Hill House) that were complete enough to map
column18617: and eventually uncovered twelve houses of the Isin-Larsa/Old Babylonian period. There were many graves beneath the floors and tablets were also relatively common. Most of the tablets have to do with the business of the temple
column18618: so the houses here probably belonged to temple workers.\r\n\r\nWoolley named the streets he found in areas EM and AH. He felt that by naming the streets he could more easily identify any particular house
column18619: giving them numbers along the street with odd numbers on one side and even on the other. Many of the street names recur in the English city of Bath
column18620: where Woolley owned a house.\r\n\r\nThe northern portion of area EM ('Quality Lane' on Woolley's map) was excavated as area DP in season 4. This was higher ground than much of the rest of EM and is mapped with only partial houses that are not published in any detail. The houses of EM are more completely published
column18621: but their various phases of construction and rebuilding are not detailed. The domestic space represented by these houses likely continued eastward into area EH in the Isin-Larsa/Old Babylonian and Kassite periods
column18622: then was cut through and partly destroyed by the foundations of the Neo-Babylonian temenos wall."

column24230: property_value:"That its foundation goes back behind the Third Dynasty of Ur is certain
column24231: for fragments of walls\r\nand pavements in pIano-convex brick (PI. 30a) prove the fact
column24232: but of the character of that original structure nothing can be said. Ur-Nammu was responsible for the temple in its existing form; he built it in mud brick
column24233: or at any rate made much use of that material
column24234: and his work was added to and probably completed by his son Dungi. Bur-Sin\r\nreplaced with burnt brick the mud-brick walls of his grandfather and Gimil-Sin added further details. The temple was\r\ncompletely overthrown by the Elamites on the occasion of the downfall of Ibi-Sin and under the Isin Dynasty was rebuilt by Gimil-ilishu
column24235: who faithfully followed the lines of the Third Dynasty ground-plan. Ishme-Dagan
column24237: \r\nand Sin-idinnam all in turn undertook repairs of its structure and Kudur-Mabug seems to have done some more radical restoration
column24238: but his building was destroyed by the Babylonians in the time of Samsu-iluna. It was probably\r\nrestored after a fashion not much later
column24239: but the first actual record of its re-establishment is that of Kuri-Galzu; the\r\nKassite ruler still kept to the original plan
column24240: but added a few new features. His building was repaired
column24242: by Marduk-nadin-ahhe in the 11th century B.C. Nebuchadnezzar was the first to tamper seriously with the ancient ground-plan; his reconstruction involved a complete change of character corresponding to\r\na change of ritual in the temple services
column24243: and in the temple as he left it the old E-nun-mah is barely recognisable. Nabonidus repaired but does not seem to have modified his predecessor's work. Finally we find
column24245: remains of a further reconstruction which we can attribute only to Cyrus of Persia."
column24249: property_value:"The building was an almost exact square measuring some 57.00 m. in either direction; its angles were
column24251: \r\norientated to the cardinal points of the compass. It was surrounded by a wall 2.70 m. thick strengthened by double\r\nbuttresses
column24252: of which there were five on each side
column24253: and the area thus enclosed was raised to form a platform about 2.00 m. above the level of the ground outside; this wall is fairly well preserved on the NE (v. Pis. 28b.
column24256: and is partly masked by subsequent additions in the SE (PI. 29a)
column24257: could be traced only by its\r\nfoundations on the SW
column24258: where the building has been remodelled
column24259: and on the NW it has been completely eradicated by a drain of Nebuchadnezzar. There is a doorway in the SE wall which
column24261: would seem to have led only into\r\ntwo small chambers having no communication with the rest of the building. In view of the denudation of the walls
column24262: \r\nwhich here do not rise above floor level
column24263: it is not possible to assert definitely that such communication never\r\nexisted
column24264: but the facts that the wall between rooms 17 and 18 is  whereas in almost every other case the doorways can be distinguished even at this level (rooms 8
column24267: and that no hinge-box or doorsocket stone was found here
column24268: make the theory of a door hazardous. Probably the real entrance to the building\r\nwas in the NW front."
column24288: property_value:"The abbreviation ES almost certainly stands for Enunmah South
column24289: though it may also have to do with the building called emuriana
column24290: referenced in a disturbed Kassite door socket found in the area. Legrain lists ES as the Egigpar of Nabonidus
column24292: but he almost certainly meant the Enunmah of Nabonidus. The abbreviation ES first appeared in season one as a supplement to Trial Trench B (TTB.ES) when the trench was expanded to reveal the extents of the building found to be called e-nun-mah. In season 3
column24293: the abbreviation shortened simply to ES
column24294: used for the majority of the enunmah building.\r\n\r\nThe Enunmah changed in layout and likely in usage through the many centuries of its existence. Initially a storage building called the ga-nun-mah
column24295: it seems to have been used as a temple
column24297: in the Neo-Babylonian period.\r\n\r\nSome lists of excavation abbreviations equate ES with the Dublalmah site. This is because the southern Enunmah is just east of the Dublalmah. Area ESB is still more closely associated with the eastern edge of the dublalmah."
column24567: footnote:"Data collected by British Museum research team"}]}
column24636: property_value:"TTB is shorthand for Trial Trench B
column24637: one of two trenches excavated in Woolley's first season at Ur in 1922. This one was about 3.5 meters wide by about 60 meters long and ended up almost entirely within the e-nun-mah
column24638: a building that went through many forms over the centuries. The trench was expanded to reveal the building and extra abbreviations were added to it to indicate portions
column24639: roughly in directional notation from the main trench. The trench cut the building close to the west corner and TTB.W became the abbreviation for this area beyond the trench itself. TTB.SS and TTB.ES covered the larger area to the south and east. The abbreviation ES was then used in later seasons to refer to the majority of the building and a small portion of the area to the south of it.\r\n\r\nThe enunmah itself was a complicated structure that seems to have changed function from storeroom (originally called the ganunmah) to temple through its long history. Woolley began assigning room numbers within the abbreviation TTB
column24640: but these excavation room numbers do not correlate precisely with the published room numbers."
column24660: property_value:"(See PI. 32b) Except at the NW end of the room virtually nothing of the burnt-brick wall survived. Against the western jamb of the door in the NW wall was a doorsocket stone
column24662: for the insertion of which the mudbrick wall has been cut back; part of the brick hinge-box remains and the mud floor can be traced running above the bricks of the box
column24663: from which fact one can conclude that the socket-stone belongs to the Kassite restoration. The mud floor
column24664: flush with the middle of the fourth course of wall bricks
column24665: was much destroyed; at the NW end there were traces of a brick pavement above it
column24666: for which it may have served as a foundation. There was a brick threshold across the doorway
column24667: and against the northern jamb a brick with a hole through it had been used as an impost for the door frame. Tablets found here included one dated in the 7th year of Gungunum of Larsa (U. 318)."
column24703: property_value:"In the west corner there was in the core of the wall a brick with the Kudur-Mabug stamp; it was possibly re-used but is more probably original and dates the lower part of the wall to the Larsa period. The floor had disappeared
column24704: owing to the fact that the Neo-Babylonian floor had been laid at the same level in this as in the other rooms of the sanctuary. The room had been partly cleared by Taylor and had suffered severely from exposure since then. Under the Neo-Babylonian pavement
column24705: against the inner side of the entrance door
column24706: there was a doorsocket stone of Marduk-nadin-ahhe. 76 Loose in the lower earth filling there were found a large oval blue paste pendant (U. 8335)
column24707: an object like a spoon-bowl of white steatite (U. 8336)
column24709: and a crescent-shaped amulet of red pebble (U. 8334)."
column24729: property_value:"Against the NW jamb of the door in the NE wall
column24733: 80). In the filling was found a broken mud brick with the stamp of Kudur-Mabug and also in the filling was a very large inscribed stone duck-weight (U. 808). A doorsocket of Kuri-Galzu (U. 950) was not in situ
column24734: nor was a fragment of a clay cone of Nur-Adad (U. 335). On a fragmentary vessel of limestone was a dedication by Sin- ... - uballit (U. 873). The tablets were U. 739
column24735: 740. To the NW of rooms 23 and 24 all traces of the building had disappeared and a shaft sunk between those rooms and the Nebuchadnezzar drain failed to find even the foundations of walls. Below the level of the drain came hard-packed brick earth
column24737: in which (at depth 2.00 m.) was found a late carnelian cylinder seal (U. 775
column24740: proving that the layer was relatively late. From 2.20 m. to 3.20 m. was sand
column24741: and then a floor of grey clay thinly overlaid with white plaster
column24742: this connecting with First Dynasty of Ur levels found farther to the west. Below this was mixed soil going down to 3.80 m. and then clean sandy soil to 5.30 m. In the top levels SE of the drain and not disturbed by its construction were found a fragment of an inscribed diorite vessel (U. 874
column24744: a fragment of a small inscribed stone macehead (U. 985)
column24745: and a considerable number of clay tablets (U. 381-86
column24755: the former including examples dated to the 3rd year of Gimil-Sin
column24759: and to the reign of Samsu-iluna; one seal impression was that of A-ab-ba
column24762: perhaps the Enannatum who built the Gig-Par-Ku in the reign of Gungunum. A certain number of objects were found either against the walls of the building
column24764: or in the rubbish which overlay its ruins. A roughly made cup of reddish-drab clay with a pierced base (Type IV) seemed to belong to the Kuri-Galzu stratum; stone vase fragments with inscriptions (fragmentary) of Rimush (U. 1167) and Dungi (U. 296) and of an unknown dedicator
column24765: an inscribed fragment of a statue in diorite (U. 744)
column24766: a fragment in dolerite of a wig (?) for application to a statue (U. 176)
column24767: a shell amulet in the form of a demon's head (U. 233)
column24777: including examples dated to the 8th year of Bur-Sin and the 2nd year of Abi-sare (U. 373
column24794: property_value:"This is the excavation area south of area ES
column24795: beyond the southernmost wall of the enunmah and just east of the dublalmah. It was in this area that a door socket of Kurigalzu mentioning a building called the emuriana was found and Woolley attempted to uncover this building here. The socket was not found in its original position
column24797: and Woolley eventually felt that the emuriana building was never in this location or that it had been completely destroyed. What he found in the area was mostly related to the enunmah or were scattered walls that were very difficult to follow. Indeed
column24798: this area of the temenos zone
column24799: from the eastern edge of the dublalmah to the northeast wall of the Neobabylonian temenos wall
column24800: was badly denuded. Area ES/ESB was sometimes equated with the dublalmah because it was initially thought that building may have extended here."
column24812: property_value:"Front of Hall's excavation area B"
column24820: property_value:"The excavation area abbreviation FH stands for 'Front of Hall'. By this
column24821: Woolley meant the area in front of (north of) Hall's excavation area B
column24822: the building found to be the ehursag. Woolley dug Trial Trench C (TTC) in the southern extent of this denuded area in season 4 and expanded investigations in seasons 9 and 10 in order to complete his understanding of the constructions inside the temenos and especially to find more evidence of the earlier temenos wall.\r\n\r\nIn a season 9 report early in 1931
column24823: Woolley had this to say about what he found in area FH: \"considerable Larsa wall
column24824: some Kassite house remains of no particular importance
column24825: and a remarkable cistern of burnt bricks and bitumen.\" In season 10
column24826: he said: \"Having proved that nothing could be recovered in this area to complete the ground-plan of the Temenos I stopped the work.\""
column24842: property_value:"Area abbreviation LH refers to the excavation of a ancient (Larsa period?) pit mostly filled with broken pottery that sat in front of the eastern portion of the Third Dynasty temenos wall. The pit is inside area FH but appears to have been given its own abbreviation. Legrain lists the context as
column24843: \"Pit in front of third dynasty wall\" and one of the field catalog cards says similarly
column24844: \"mixed rubbish in the pit in front of the IIIrd Dynasty wall.\" UE 6 discusses this rubbish pit briefly in connection with the Ur III temenos stating that the pit was located in site grid square Y 37."
column24864: property_value:"The excavation area given the abbreviation KP was eventually found to be the site of the ancient building known as the giparu (alternatively e-gig-par or gig-par-ku). Mostly dedicated to the goddess Nin-gal
column24866: it was also in various periods the residence of the entu priestess. The abbreviation KP
column24868: stands for King's Palace because Woolley initially thought this might be the site of Shulgi's palace
column24869: the ehursag.\r\n\r\nThe giparu was a very long-lived building
column24870: though it underwent many changes over many centuries. Most striking were the changes in the Neo-Babylonian period when Woolley shows it combining with the dublalmah to the east. He believed that by this point the building was not sufficient to house the Ningal temple and the entu priestess together
column24871: and thus the so-called Palace of Belshaltinannar was constructed outside the temenos specifically to house the priestess herself.\r\n\r\nAt times Woolley refers to the giparu as the Great Ningal Temple
column24872: which can be confusing as the Kassite and Neo-Bablyonian Ningal temples had moved onto the ziggurat terrace to the north of the giparu (Area HD). Furthermore
column24873: parts of the giparu were excavated under area abbreviations other than KP in season 3 when the full extents of the building were only just coming to light. The northern portion originally carried the abbreviation HDB and the southeastern portion
column24894: property_value:"The excavation area abbreviation HDB refers to the southern extension of area HD
column24895: thus it is beyond Hall's Dump
column24896: or south of the pile of back-dirt on the southern ziggurat terrace. Many of the artifact cards that have this context designation mention 'lower rooms' and it is apparent that the southern extension HDB uncovered walls at a lower elevation because they were off of the ziggurat terrace. This makes HDB actually the northern part of area KP (the giparu)
column24897: also begun in season 3. Only one season 4 artifact has the abbreviation HD
column24898: and it sits among many other cards from KP."
column24918: property_value:"The excavation area abbreviation SF refers to the southeastern portion of the giparu (KP). This building was very large and in season 3 its full extents were not yet known. It was being excavated from the north and the south
column24919: thus it initially received different abbreviations. SF may stand for South Face or South Front
column24920: though this is nowhere recorded. Legrain records \"Gipar-ku
column24921: SE part\" for this context. The shape of the giparu changed through the centuries and SF runs to join with the dublalmah to the east
column24922: as that building merged with the giparu in the Neo-Babylonian period."
column25010: property_value:"The sanctuary stood as a complete and independent entity.  Rooms and courts are all interconnected
column25012: the E.NUN. It has a similar plan to private houses with added features like washing places
column25018: and economic tablets attest to a varied activities involved in running an estate."

column27749: property_value:"The meaning of this two-letter designation is unclear. It may derive from Woolley's search for Shulgi's palace and may thus stand for Palace of Dungi. Woolley came to realize
column27751: that it was an enormous courtyard surrounded by rooms
column27752: and at times in the excavation it was simply referred to as the Ziggurat Courtyard. The path through the court led to the ziggurat terrace and eventually to the temple atop it. The court was likely a gathering place for special occasions of worship to the moon god (whose name Woolley read Nannar
column27753: but which we read today as Nanna). Therefore
column27754: Woolley eventually dubbed this space the Great Nannar Courtyard.\r\n\r\nArea PD is the large space to the east of the ziggurat terrace
column27755: substantially lower in elevation than the base of the ziggurat. It had many floors over many periods. It consisted of a large paved courtyard (some 50 x 75 meters) surrounded by rooms that may have been used for storage. Because of indentations in some of the wall faces
column27756: Woolley believed there was once an inset wooden colonnade along some of the walls."
column27772: property_value:"The excavation area abbreviation PS probably stood for Palace Stores and refers to the series of magazine-like rooms surrounding the Great Nanna Courtyard. Woolley originally coded the region of the courtyard as PD
column27774: since he felt it might have been a palace. The series of rooms surrounding the courtyard may well have been for storage
column27775: but Woolley came to realize that the building itself was not a palace. The abbreviation PS appears on several season 3 catalog cards
column27776: but no explanation of its meaning occurs anywhere. Legrain lists PR as the magazines around the courtyard
column27777: but this was probably a mistyped reference for PS since PR does not appear as an abbreviation on any of Woolley's cards."
column27817: property_value:"Harbour Temple; Nebuchadrezzar Temple outside NE side of Temenos"
column27821: property_value:"The Harbor Temple had no field abbreviation
column27822: probably because HT was already in use and because very few artifacts were found within. Despite being largely empty
column27823: this building was described by Woolley as one of the best preserved temples of the Neo-Babylonian period in Mesopotamia. \r\n\r\nThe temple covered 33x27 meters and some of the bricks in its walls bore the inscription of Nebuchadnezzar. Nonetheless
column27824: Woolley suggested Nabonidus as the more likely founder. The walls were of mud brick with baked brick facing up to a meter thick and they stood to a height of 6.5 meters. The entire building was filled with clean sand and Woolley proposed that it was
column27826: not the actual temple but a complete replica beneath the surface never intended for human use. The actual temple would have stood above and it had completely eroded away. Evidence for the upper temple was found in a few paving bricks of Nabonidus at a level equivalent to the floor of the nearby 'Palace of Belshaltinannar'. In fact
column27827: Woolley suggested that the Harbor Temple may have been a chapel specifically associated with this building.\r\n\r\nCreating such a substructure has apparent (much earlier) textual but not archaeological precedent. Woolley believed that after the sub-temple was complete
column27828: it was consecrated to the gods and then filled with sand
column27829: then an entire temple built again above it for human use. No indication of the deity to whom the temple was dedicated was found.\r\n\r\nThe temple was first uncovered at the end of season 8 and a temporary wooden roof was erected to keep it from filling in during summer sandstorms. So roofed
column27830: it appeared remarkably complete and Woolley suggested it be preserved this way for tourists to experience."
column27902: property_value:"This excavation area was designated Kings Palace South (KPS) because it explored walls that were south of the main giparu building (KP). Some of these late walls cut into earlier levels of the giparu in its southern portion. The walls were found to be of patchwork domestic structures
column27903: two houses (A to the south and B to the north) separated by a street (scanty remains of a House C were also found). They were formed mostly of broken and reused bricks of the Larsa/Old Babylonian period and probably dated to the Kassite period
column27904: repaired and reused into the Neo-Babylonian. Beneath these walls were found indications of the earlier Temenos wall and various artifacts of the Early Dynastic period.\r\n\r\nThe excavation area overall included part of the Neo-Babylonian temenos wall to the west
column27905: the part that contained the Nebuchadnezzar gate where inscribed bricks of this king were uncovered in foundation boxes. It stretched southward to the edge of the excavation areas called EH and DP."
column27921: property_value:"Domestic House dating to the Kassite Period.  SE side of a street.  Walls were often altered and patched."
column28009: property_value:"Mud lined floor with drains  and sealings of Ibbi-Suen."
column28037: property_value:"Destroyed by Temenos Wall.  Unknown function."
column28081: property_value:"Addition to original plan. Mud floor with large clay jars."
column28109: property_value:"Roughly paved room step down possibly store room with hoard of objects."
column28138: includes fireplace and drains.  Possible Audience Chamber"
column28166: property_value:"The best preserved house in the KPS site.  "
column28247: much ruined.  Field cards say maybe a kiln/furnace
column28272: property_value:"The excavation abbreviation LT is recorded on only one artifact from season 3. The abbreviation probably stands for Lower Town or something to that effect since this area is found outside the walls of Ur
column28273: about 800 meters southwest of the ziggurat. Woolley sent a crew to excavate here for one day in season 3
column28274: uncovering partial remains of a small building
column28275: but little else. The building was never published and the only record of it is in a report dated November 15
column28276: 1924: \"A small gang were set to test the character of a site lying some nine hundred yards SW of the Ziggurat
column28278: where Mr. Gadd had remarked large bricks of a type unusual at Ur and possibly of Sargonid date. One day's work sufficed for this spot; a small building was found here
column28279: but it had been denuded by weather below floor level
column28280: nor was there anything left to indicate its period; the work was therefore abandoned.\""

column28312: property_value:"Mausoleum of Dungi; Shulgi Mausoleum; Mausoleum Site"
column28316: property_value:"Woolley called the east corner of the Neo-Babylonian temenos the Bur-Sin Corner (area BC) because he found bricks of Bur-Sin (now read Amar-Sin or Amar-Suen) there in early season explorations.\r\n\r\nArea BC is particularly complex because it consists of substantial building in many periods. The largest building was of the Ur III period
column28317: and it is this building to which the abbreviation BC typically refers in field notes. It sits at the northeastern edge of the Royal Cemetery. The main Ur III building was 35 x 27m and its southwest wall was preserved two meters in height
column28318: while its northeast wall was largely destroyed. Its walls were built with inscribed bricks of Shulgi. The overall layout of the building is much like a courtyard house but on a large scale and with more ritual furnishings. Attached to this building were two annexes
column28319: one northwest and the other southeast
column28320: built with bricks of Shulgi's son
column28321: Amar-Sin (see context AD). Beneath the entire building were three very large vaults. All of them had been plundered in antiquity and only scattered fragments of artifacts and bones were discovered inside. Nonetheless
column28322: Woolley believed that these vaults originally held the remains of the Ur III kings. For this reason
column28323: area BC is sometimes referred to as the Mausoleum Site.\r\n\r\nThe building was destroyed by Elamites
column28325: and sometime thereafter houses of the Isin-Larsa/Old Babylonian period were constructed in the area (see House 30). Finally
column28326: the Neo-Babylonian Temenos wall was constructed over and through parts of the remains."
column28346: property_value:"Five houses of the Isin-Larsa/Old Babylonian period infringed upon the ruins of the Shulgi Mausoleum and its Amar-Sin annexes. In fact
column28347: the houses were built almost directly above its remains and it is curious to think that the large and important mausolea would have faded so completely from memory that houses would be built here 100 - 200 years later. Woolley felt that the Elamite destruction had been severe enough to accomplish this.\r\n\r\nThe southwest wall of the mausolea remained to a height of 2 meters while the northeast wall was substantially ruined and it is this northeastern side that is most heavily built over. Woolley excavated these houses quickly in his effort to uncover the larger Ur III structure and numbered them as one unit
column28348: House 30. Later he separated the plans into individual houses
column28349: labeled House 30 A-E. All were badly denuded and few finds came from them
column28350: though typically there were also graves beneath the floors that are better recorded. These and drainpipes often disturbed parts of the ruined mausolea below."

column30446: property_value:"The excavation area abbreviation AD was apparently duplicated by accident and thus refers to two different areas of the site. Legrain reported the abbreviation as \"Annex of Dungi's Tomb
column30447: \" but he was not on site the year that the context was excavated. He placed the abbreviation with this meaning on cards he created for inscribed material that came to him in the museum. Some tablets and cylinder seals were found in the filling of the tomb annex and some even have a note that they are from Seal Impression Strata against the tomb or its foundational fill. These artifacts are clearly from the BC area
column30448: that of the Mausoleum of the Ur III kings built by Shulgi and his son Amar-Sin (Amar-Suen).\r\n\r\nAmar-Sin built two annexes onto the Shulgi building (See area BC)
column30449: one to the northwest and the other to the southeast. It is not clear which of the two annexes Legrain was referring to with the abbreviation AD
column30450: probably either or both. Essentially artifacts from this use of AD can only be located generally to the overall BC area at the eastern edge of the Royal Cemetery (PG).\r\n\r\nOn the excavation site the abbreviation AD was being used for the so-called Palace of Bel-Shalti-Nannar. Artifacts from the two separate AD contexts have been divided in the digital data wherever possible."

column31237: property_value:"The excavation area abbreviation NH refers to the better-preserved Neo-Babyloninan Housing immediately southwest of area AH (though at one point Legrain mistakenly listed it as North Harbour). Woolley excavated in area NH for a short time in season 9 and again for an even shorter time (\"a few days at the end of the season\" according to field reports) in season 12. He did not dig below the level of Neo-Babylonian housing as his goal was to expose the layout of a portion of the Neo-Babylonian town. Across much of the site
column31238: the Neo-Babylonian domestic remains were badly preserved and even here there were only the stubs of walls and some evidence of later
column31240: occupation. The houses used no baked brick and they were close to the surface
column31241: thus they had often disappeared almost completely. Nonetheless
column31242: Woolley recovered outlines of two streets and seven houses along with a number of late artifacts
column31243: including two pots filled with tablets dating from the reign of Nabopolassar up to that of Alexander the Great.\r\n\r\nNeo-Babylonian houses were much more spacious in ground plan than Old Babylonian and were typically built with a saw-toothed outer plan that Woolley had difficulty explaining. The streets were much more linear than earlier layouts and this implies developments in centralized town planning. Woolley attributed this entire domestic quarter
column31244: which he believed had been built on ground cleared of all other remains
column31245: to the time of Nebuchadnezzar.\r\n\r\nDespite the fact that there were many artifacts recovered here and there were many graves excavated
column31246: there are only four field notecards extant and only cursory publication. When reporting graves
column31248: not room. Even the house numbers were assigned late
column31249: as evidenced by publication in UE9
column31250: which discusses House A and B while its map numbers 1-7. Houses 6 and 7 were certainly dug in 1931 when Woolley intended to extend area AH
column31251: but he changed his mind and only later went back to uncover the outlines of a few more houses south of these in the final season
column31695: property_value:"This area lies beyond (north/northwest of) Nebuchadnezzar's corner fort (NCF) at the west corner of the temenos wall. In seasons 10 and 11 the area was somewhat systematically excavated
column31696: initially creating a shallow trench from the northwest terrace and temenos wall almost to the city wall some 100 meters away. According to the 1932 reports
column31697: it was \"enlarged into a regular excavation covering the area of a number of houses
column31698: \" and this expansion was continued in season 11. Excavations were taken through Persian (mostly surface) level down only a small depth to relatively well preserved house remains of the late Kassite and Neo-Babylonian periods. Many of the houses had graves under their floors. Woolley did not map or record the houses or graves
column31699: saying in his Antiquaries Journal report for 1932 (p.390): \"They produced no objects of importance
column31700: but the graves did yield a certain number of glazed vases
column31701: beads and seals.\"\r\n\r\nPublication does not do justice to the extent of this excavation area. Only XNCF
column31702: a smaller excavation of domestic space along the NW temenos is published in UE8 and that in only a few paragraphs."

column31980: property_value:"The excavation area abbreviation NTB refers to that space beyond (northeast of
column31981: toward the central portion of the mound of Ur) the Ningizzida temple on the southwest city wall. Woolley often used the suffix letter B to indicate an extension of an excavation area
column31982: particularly one that went beyond the confines of a visible building he was excavating. He rarely explains
column31984: just how far away from the building the extended excavation was carried out. In this case
column31985: Woolley explored late remains that surrounded the Ningizzida temple
column31986: noting that there were Neo-Babylonian and Persian house remains and burials nearby. Most of these are likely from area NTB
column31987: though Woolley only preceded the grave number with NT and some late graves did infringe upon the temple building itself.\r\n\r\nThere are very few artifacts that actually display the NTB designation and these are all from season 8. The excavation area outside the temple space may not have been large
column31988: though it is impossible to tell on current evidence."
column32068: property_value:"The excavation area abbreviation AD was apparently duplicated by accident and thus refers to two different areas of the site. At the excavation
column32069: the designation was used to refer to a large Neo-Babylonian structure in the northern portion of the site that was eventually dubbed the 'Palace of Bel-Shalti-Nannar.' The horizontal extent of this building is one of the largest at Ur and the layout resembles that of the 'Great House' in Merkes at Babylon. The building's foundations were preserved to a great depth (over 3 meters) and paved floors sat at the top of the intentional fill of these foundations. Walls did not extend much above this level and excavation consisted mostly of following the outlines in order to determine the ground plan. A few artifacts were recovered
column32070: primarily from intrusive graves and from foundation deposits.\r\n\r\nInscribed bricks in the preserved floor led Woolley to identify the building with the residence of the entu priestess in the Neo-Babylonian period. It was built for the daughter of Nabonidus
column32071: whose name we now read as Ennigaldi-Nanna but which in Woolley's day was read Bel-Shalti-Nannar. It may have had some administrative functions but it mainly appears to have been a large-scale residence.\r\n\r\nLegrain
column32072: in his museum work on inscribed materials
column32073: used the excavation area abbreviation AD to refer to a subsection of area BC (the mausoleum of the Ur III kings). Artifacts from the two separate AD contexts have been divided in the digital data wherever possible."
column32122: property_value:"Pit F stands apart from the Royal Cemetery pits dug in the preceding year
column32123: despite its letter 'F' falling inside the sequence of those pits. The sequence of pit letters was assigned after most had been dug
column32124: probably in season 8 as confusion arose over pits I and J. Pit F was originally called PFT to distinguish it from pits in the Royal Cemetery area. The suffix T probably stood for Temenos to show that Pit F was dug in the area inside the early temenos wall. The abbreviation became confusing and Legrain reports PF as 'Flood Pit' and PFT as 'Shaft in town area
column32125: ' but the two designations are actually identical.\r\n\r\nThe term 'Flood Pit' was often used to refer to Pit F because of the deep layers of silt found near its deepest extent. As much as 3 meters thickness of fine water-lain soil was encountered here
column32126: evidence of a great flood. In his books and talks for the general public
column32127: Woolley often made the equation of this flood with the biblical flood
column32128: but in his academic discussions he never did. Instead
column32129: here he referred to the frequent flooding of the Euphrates and how this particular flood must have been large and may have spawned Sumerian legends.\r\n\r\nPit F was extremely large and extremely deep. Woolley's intent was to reach the earliest occupation of the site. He chose an already low-lying zone neighboring the excavation area EH and laid out a trench 15x25 meters
column32130: though in the southern half he only dug 10 meters width
column32131: making the final pit L shaped. He truncated the horizontal extent further as he dug down to avoid collapse and he eventually reached a depth of some 19 meters from the surface of the mound. The top of the pit had already been denuded to the Early Dynastic levels and thus late material was typically not found here. From the surface
column32132: Woolley found eight levels of early building remains going deeper and deeper. Beneath this he found pottery kilns and a deep layer of over-fired pottery fragments indicating manufacture. Near the bottom of this stratum he began finding Uruk period graves (that he called Jemdat Nasr period graves). He labeled these not with numbers
column32133: but with letters in the sequence PFG/A through PFG/XX. Below this he encountered the flood layer with Ubaid period graves cut into it. Beneath the flood layer he found evidence of Ubaid habitation near sea level and what he believed to be indications of the early marshlands in which Ur had originally been a very low mound."
column32353: property_value:"Designation of a square dug inside PFT"
column32981: property_value:"The excavation area abbreviation PG grew to refer to a large region
column32983: in the southeastern portion of the Neo-Babylonian temenos but below the level of that wall. The area is most often referred to as the Royal Cemetery. The abbreviation PG
column32985: was initially used to designate individual graves: PG1422
column32987: refers to Private Grave number 1422. The first PG numbers were assigned in season 5 when a series of trial trenches (see TTD
column32990: and TTG) were excavated in the area. These trenches were expanded to uncover more and more graves over the next few seasons. The last number assigned in the PG sequence was around 1850 but numbers were often reassigned for publication and even in the field some numbers were combined as they were recognized to come from one large grave rather than two separate ones. Others were deemed to fragmentary to publish; furthermore
column32991: several hundred additional graves were found in Pit X
column32992: an expansion of the PG area dug in 1934. The total number of graves excavated in the Royal Cemetery is thus extremely difficult to determine. Woolley reports that there may once have been as many as three times the total number of graves he recorded
column32993: as he found many plundered and almost completely destroyed.\r\n\r\nDespite being called the Royal Cemetery
column32994: there were only 16 graves that Woolley actually dubbed 'royal.' He believed that these formed the core of the burial ground and that many other people wanted to be buried nearby. The cemetery lay outside of the original temenos
column32996: and was apparently a dumping ground through much of its history. Stratigraphic layers of sealings (see SIS) help to date the main period of the Royal Cemetery to the Early Dynastic III
column32997: though there are also graves of the Akkadian and perhaps some of the early Ur III period here. Well beneath the main PG area are also graves of the Uruk and Ubaid periods
column32998: but these were mainly uncovered in pits dug within or adjacent to area PG (see PJ
column33001: Pit Y and Pit Z).\r\n\r\nMost burials in area PG were simple inhumations with few artifacts
column33002: but the ones Woolley called royal were much more elaborate. Apart from having rich artifacts
column33003: they also showed evidence of human sacrifice -- many bodies were found in 'death pits' outside the main 'royal' burial. The people found in these death pits may have been attendants who went into the afterlife with their king or queen
column33004: yet no other indication of this practice is found elsewhere in Mesopotamia. Nor do we know who these 'kings and queens' were. The dating of the graves makes it difficult to associate them with a known dynasty at Ur and there were very few names found with any of the bodies. Only the burial of Puabi
column33006: can be directly identified by her cylinder seal and she does not appear on any king list. References to Mesannepada and his wife Ninbanda
column33007: a king and queen of the first dynasty of Ur
column33008: were found but not in specific graves. Instead
column33009: they were found in material above the main graves and would imply that the royal tombs pre-date the first dynasty.\r\n\r\nWoolley spent a great deal of time and energy excavating the Royal Cemetery and the majority of his field notes concern it. Recording of contexts here
column33011: is better than anywhere else at Ur. Nonetheless
column33012: not all of the graves were mapped and photographs were often difficult to obtain."

column33666: Woolley excavated a series of pits within the Royal Cemetery. He had already cut this area down about 10 meters from the surface
column33667: so it was an ideal location to go deeper to investigate the earliest occupation of the site. The only map of the location of these pits that Woolley published is found in Ur Excavations volume 4 in 1955
column33668: but it is demonstrably unreliable. Combining information from the field notes
column33670: and the UE4 stratigraphic profile helps to get closer to the actual sizes and locations
column33671: but most of these cannot be taken as exact.\r\n\r\nPit A was located relatively centrally in the overall Royal Cemetery Area
column33672: though its exact location is not known. A reference in the Antiquaries Journal for 1929 mentions a pit dug somewhat northwest of Pit B on the \"other side of PG/1237\" and this must be Pit A as no other pit would fit the description. This helps to narrow the location as does the fitting of lines from the combined stratigraphic profile published in UE4. Everything points to a location west-nortwest of PG/1237. The plan map published in 1955 shows Pit A substantially southwest of this
column33673: but it is not trustworthy. The stratigraphic profile places the width of the pit at 2 meters and it is probably safe to assume that it was square. It began at the same level as the floor of PG/1237 and went down at least another 5 meters
column33674: reaching 1.5 meters above sea level. No artifacts are recorded as having been collected from this pit."

column33873: property_value:"Pit W was excavated from the bottom of area PG near Pits Y and Z in order to more fully explore the Seal Impression Strata discovered running across the cemetery. Since these strata contained so many early seals and tablets it was clear that they were essential for dating the graves and for learning more about the administration of the city of Ur. In order to observe the strata more clearly
column33874: Pit W was much larger than most exploratory pits in the cemetery region
column33875: laid out to be 15x7 meters. It was dug from the northeast side of PG/1631 but its horizontal extents were not mapped. Its published stratigraphic profile shows that PG/1631 was actually somewhere near the middle of the long side of the trench and Woolley states that Pit W was placed so as to virtually fill the gap between Pits Y and Z
column33876: but was set a few meters northeast of them. This allows for a relatively accurate placement of the pit. \r\n\r\nPit W quickly ran through the seal impression strata but Woolley continued it down much farther
column33877: as he had with Pits Y and Z
column33878: to reach about a meter below sea level. He thus uncovered many graves earlier than the main Royal Cemetery
column33879: and because he believed them to be from the Jemdet Nasr period
column33880: he began JNG numbers for them. This discovery
column33881: combined with early graves in Pit Y
column33882: spawned the conception of a Jemdet Nasr cemetery running beneath and south of the Royal Cemetery
column33883: and in season 12 Woolley would seek to expose it in Pit X."
column35392: Woolley expanded the Royal Cemetery (area PG) to the southwest and northeast. After digging more of the southwestern extent
column35393: he decided to investigate deeper still in two pits larger than those he dug in season 7 but not as large as Pit F in the Temenos area. These two pits were initially Pits I and J in the sequence but confusion with lettering caused Woolley to begin at the end of the alphabet and rename these pits Y and Z.\r\n\r\nPit I was located northwest of Pit J along the southwestern line of the Royal Cemetery excavation and was quickly renamed Pit Z. There are very few references to Pit I in the field records. Legrain lists PIG as a pit near PFT and the final letter G shows that it was within the Royal Cemetery area rather than the Temenos area. Pit Z is about 50 meters southeast of Pit F. The published stratigraphic profile shows it to be 6 meters wide at the top and 4 meters wide at the bottom. Its sides sloped in order to prevent collapse. It reached just below sea level and it revealed more of the seal impression strata that ran through the cemetery. This pit and Pit Y both uncovered graves earlier than the Royal Cemetery main burials. These graves were eventually given JNG numbers
column35394: a continuous sequence across Pits W

column58107: Woolley expanded his trial trenches in area PG opening up a much larger space in the Royal Cemetery proper. The northeastern extents in TTG had been revealing fewer and fewer graves
column58108: so he expected many more to the southeast; indeed
column58109: he found an increasing density here. He no longer considered this to be trial exploration
column58111: and thus began to call the space the Private Graves Area
column58112: abbreviated PGA. He also began mapping individual graves
column58113: establishing at least 4 mapping points from which he took angular measures to pinpoint locations. Unfortunately he never showed where these stakes were placed on any map so we can no longer utilize the recorded angles. \r\n\r\nCards from this season that bear the abbreviation PGA all concern textual material. column66671: property_value:"Pit X was excavated as a large southern extension of the Royal Cemetery area

column72478: property_value:"Essentially a suburb of the ancient city
column72479: this area is located about 2 km to the northeast of the ziggurat of Ur. The precise extents of Diqdiqqeh were never defined
column72480: but Woolley referred to it as the low ground between the main railway line and the branch that went to Nasiriyeh. The train lines no longer run in the same place they did in Woolley's day
column72481: but Corona images allow us to recreate their paths. This makes the general boundaries west
column72483: and east somewhat known but how far it stretched north is not completely clear.\r\n\r\nFrom the first season workers walking across this area picked up surface finds and brought them to Woolley. At that time the location did not have a fixed name in Woolley's mind and thus first season references sometimes say 'near the railway' or 'near Munshid's water engine.' In the second season Woolley decided to investigate more systematically
column72484: but after two days of excavation he decided there was not enough remaining architecture to reward further work. Instead
column72485: he continued to allow the workers to gather finds over the next ten seasons
column72486: and many later catalog cards state \"brought in: Diqdiqqeh\"\r\n\r\nThe finds from Diqdiqqeh indicate that the ancient suburb played a role in manufacturing and perhaps in commerce. Canals seem to have met in the area and boats may have unloaded goods here. Many figurines
column72488: moulds and other crafting items are among the finds
column72489: suggesting that Diqdiqqeh may have been an industrial area away from the main habitation. The so-called Treasury of Sin-Iddinam was also excavated in this general area in season 5.\r\n\r\nIn the Antiquaries Journal of January 1925
column72490: Woolley described Diqdiqqeh as follows: A mile and a half NE. of the ziggurat
column72491: between the main railway line and the Nasiriyah branch
column72492: there is a patch of low-lying ground
column72494: which the natives call Diqdiqqeh... a happy hunting-ground for treasure-seekers
column72495: and I took advantage of this fact to collect from the natives the scattered antiquities which they might bring to light."
